<br />

<BR>
三、我的觀點：<BR>
    I have never liked running. It has always been one of the things that I am really bad at. Not only do I run slowly, but I somehow could not enjoy the entire exercise. However, after reading this book, I feel that I might have a chance to change my way of running and feel the wonderful sensation to run, just like all the amazing runners in the book.<br />
<br />
    From this book, I learned an important lesson: the actual trick to run fast. Needless to say, having the correct posture, knowing how to control your breathing, and finding your own running pace are all significant aspects, but it does not end here. The mind is also essential. There is a motto that I find quite catchy - think easy, light, smooth and fast while you run. However, the most crucial factor is actually the heart. You have to truly love running. If you force yourself to run when you do not even want to, then you could never do it well. Furthermore, you cannot run only for winning, for medals, or for fame; you run because it is a thing you enjoy.<br />
<br />
    The other thing I find fascinating is an Indian tribe called Tarahumara, also known as the Raramuri or The Running People. They live deep in the Copper Canyons in Mexico. The Copper Canyons, known as Barrancas del Cobre, is like a sort of shorebound Bermuda Triangle - very few have made it out alive due to the extreme wilderness. In the Tarahumara land, there are no crimes, no war, no corruption, no greed. These Indians are the kindest and happiest people on the planet. They are the greatest runners of all time, as people put it, and their superhuman tranquillity and toughness were so unbelievable that they were considered near-mythical. The Tarahumaras are said to be able to run two full days without rest, scrambling up and down steep canyon trails like a piece of cake, while enjoying every single minute of it. How is that possible, you might ask? According to the authors research, it is because they never forget what it really feels like to love running. They remembered that running is mankinds first fine art; running was the way we survived and thrived across the planet. I cannot even imagine that there are people so inhumane and godlike before I read this book!<br />
<br />
    There is one extraordinary person mentioned in the book that I made me really interested; Dr. Joe Vigil. He is an expert at detecting crucial little details that everyone else missed. He could not outmuscle others when it comes to running, so he chose to out-science them instead. Vigil studied the tricks of timing, propulsion, leverage, as well as figuring out better ways to position his feet. I really admire his way of thinking; using an alternative way to beat other competitors. And when he has questions, he will find the answer no matter what it takes.<br />
<br />
    What surprised me the most in this book is that running shoes are not technically good for running. According to a couple of researches, more expensive shoes are more likely to make people injured. In Dr. Martis research, runners in shoes that cost more than $95 are more than twice as likely to get hurt as runners in shoes that cost less than $40. Furthermore, the cushioning in shoes actually does nothing to reduce impact. Think about it: the impact on your legs from running can be up to twelve times your body weight, and that half inch of rubber is not going to make a bit of difference. Not only that, but human beings are designed to run without shoes. Putting our feet in shoes is similar to putting them in a plaster cast. Our shoes block a natural movement of our feet when we run.<br />
<br />
    This book made quite an impact on my view of running. Not only did I learn a lot of new information, know about things that I never imagined that can exist, but also appreciate the authors way of thinking. He has such utmost curiosity, to the extent that he had risked his life multiple times just to seek the answer to a plain question. I truly hope that I can have the willpower and enthusiasm similar to the authors.<br />
<br />

